Now that we have the operating cash flow for each year, we can solve for the net present value of the project. This is necessary for the computation of the operating cash flow of the whole project. IN order to get the net present values, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Net present value}&=\dfrac{\text{Operating cashflow Year 1}}{(1+\text{required return})^1}+\dfrac{\text{Operating cashflow Year 2}}{(1+\text{required return})^2}\\
&+\dfrac{\text{Operating cashflow Year 3}}{(1+\text{required return})^3}+\dfrac{\text{Operating cashflow Year 4}}{(1+\text{required return})^4}
\end{aligned}$$

Now that we have these necessary values, we can now solve for the operating cash flow of the project using this formula for the desired net present value:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Desired net present value}&=\text{Operating cash flow} \times \text{Annuity factor}\\
&+\text{Computed net present value}-\text{Initial investment}\\
&-\text{Net working capital}+\dfrac{\text{Net working capital}+\text{After-tax salvage value}}{1.10^4}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the known value to the formula in Step 23, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\$100,000&=\text{Operating cash flow} \times \text{Annuity factor}\\
&+\$3,304,051.47-\$3,100,000\\
&-\$395,000+\dfrac{\$395,000+\$234,850}{1.10^4}
\end{aligned}$$

To solve for the bid price, we will use this formula which uses the operating cash flow as basis.

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Operating cash flow}&=[(\text{P}-\text{Variable cost})\times \text{Quantity}-\text{Fixed cost}]\times(1-\text{Tax rate})\\
&+\text{Tax rate}\times\text{Depreciation}
\end{aligned}$$

Where P is the bid price.
